		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=210#comment-12345</guid>
		<description>Spell checker does the same thing more or less using same algorithms, but not necessarily the right one. It can&#039;t spell words it doesn&#039;t know and it can&#039;t compare with what you have, which is the crux of the problem.

You&#039;re correct that referrer information is mostly useless and certainly in all cases you&#039;ve mentioned. But it doesn&#039;t cost much to check and if your visitor came from a site using descriptive URLs or from a search engine, than you might gain some insight from it.

It doesn&#039;t happen often that search engines would provide broken links, but I do stumble on broken links on other sites all the time.</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Spell checker does the same thing more or less using same algorithms, but not necessarily the right one. It can&#8217;t spell words it doesn&#8217;t know and it can&#8217;t compare with what you have, which is the crux of the problem.</p>
<p>You&#8217;re correct that referrer information is mostly useless and certainly in all cases you&#8217;ve mentioned. But it doesn&#8217;t cost much to check and if your visitor came from a site using descriptive URLs or from a search engine, than you might gain some insight from it.</p>
<p>It doesn&#8217;t happen often that search engines would provide broken links, but I do stumble on broken links on other sites all the time.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
